<h3>
            Books</h3>
<p>
            Here we have listed some examples of books that contain useful information on mental health problems such as depression and low mood that you might find helpful.</p>
<p>
            <strong>Overcoming depression and Low Mood: a five areas approach</strong> by C. Williams <a href="http://www.oupcanada.com/higher_education/publishing_partner.html">Hodder Arnold</a>; 2009. Using the established Five Areas Assessment model of depression and the evidence-based cognitive behavior therapy approach, this book covers all the issues that are known to be problematic in depression and low mood. It features interactive questions and worksheets and is presented in a clear and user-friendly format.</p>
<p>
            <strong>SOD-IT! The Depression &lsquo;Virus&rsquo; and How to Deal with it</strong> by M. Davis <a href="http://www.talkinglife.co.uk">Talking Life</a>: 2006. Written and illustrated by a mental health professional with experience of depression, this book is informative, based on research and contains practical suggestions. It is also very easy to read and dip into, with a limited amount of text and filled with cartoons that are perceptive and humorous.</p>
<p>
            <strong>I Had a Black Dog</strong> by M. Johnstone <a href="http://www.constablerobinson.com">Constable Robinson</a>: 2007. The author of &lsquo;I had a Black Dog&rsquo; experienced depression himself. Presented in picture book style, the book is accessible, witty and instructive. It provides practical advice about recognising symptoms and managing depression.&nbsp;<a href="http://www.constablerobinson.com/" target="_blank"> </a></p>
